{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644344"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:05:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:05:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18044"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18044"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10758"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59627"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"332"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8701"},{"type":"tags","id":"10201"},{"type":"tags","id":"10689"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25096"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOsgood-Schlatter disease is a condition consisting of pain and tenderness over the tibial tuberosity due to stress on the growth plate where the patellar tendon attaches.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the histological appearance of the ossification centre in this disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibrous tissue with scattered inflammatory cells","Mature lamellar bone with organised osteons","Predominance of chondrocytes and cartilage matrix","Increased number of osteoclasts and bone resorption","Presence of osteoblasts and woven bone formation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological appearance of the ossification centre in this condition is characterised by the \u003Cstrong\u003Epresence of osteoblasts and woven bone formation\u003C/strong\u003E. This reflects the active bone formation occurring at the growth plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPredominance of chondrocytes and cartilage matrix\u003C/strong\u003E would be more characteristic of the growth plate itself, rather than the ossification centre where bone formation is occurring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased number of osteoclasts and bone resorption\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a process of bone remodelling or resorption, which is not the primary feature of the ossification centre in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrous tissue with scattered inflammatory cells\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate an inflammatory process, which is not typical of the ossification centre in Osgood-Schlatter disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMature lamellar bone with organised osteons\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of mature bone, not the actively forming bone at the ossification centre in a growing child.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primary ossification centre is the first area of a bone to start ossifying.","Histologically, the primary ossification centre is characterised by the presence of osteoblasts and the formation of woven bone.","Secondary ossification centres appear after birth and contribute to the growth of long bones."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59627"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18044"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59627"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:27:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:29:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10758"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying